{{BLP sources|date=March 2011}}
'''Antone Kimball Romney''' (born August 15, 1925) is an American social sciences professor and one of the founders of [[cognitive anthropology]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2011}}  He spent most of his career at the [[University of California, Irvine]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.physorg.com/news165513181.html|title=Social scientist creates computer model to determine human perception of hues|date=29 June 2009|work=[[PhysOrg]]|accessdate=22 March 2011}}</ref>

Romney was born in [[Rexburg, Idaho]] in August 1925. He received his B.A. from  [[Brigham Young University]] (1947) in sociology, his M.A. from Brigham Young University (1948) also in sociology, his Ph.D. from [[Harvard University]] (1956) in Social Anthropology, Social Relations Department. 1955‑56 Assistant Professor, at the [[University of Chicago]]. 1957‑60 Assistant Professor, [[Stanford University]]. 1960‑66 Associate Professor, Stanford University. 1960‑65 Director, Anthropological Research, Stanford University. 1966‑68 Professor, Harvard University. 1969‑71 Dean, School of Social Sciences, University of California, Irvine. 1969-1995 Professor, University of California, Irvine. 1995- Research Professor, University of California, Irvine. 1956‑57 Fellow, Center for Advanced Study in the Behavioral Sciences, Stanford. 1994 - Fellow, [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]]. 1995- Member, [[United States National Academy of Sciences|National Academy of Sciences]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/21518029.html?dids=21518029:21518029&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jun+06%2C+1995&author=&pub=Los+Angeles+Times+(pre-1997+Fulltext)&desc=Colleges&pqatl=google|title=Colleges|date=June 6, 1995|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|page=A2|accessdate=22 March 2011}}</ref>

Kimball Romney was a son of Antone Kimball Romney (1902–1982) and a member of the [[Pratt-Romney family]].

